I"+<ul>
  <li>See Simon’s Datasette Lite announcement blog post: <a href="https://simonwillison.net/2022/May/4/datasette-lite/">Datasette Lite: a server-side Python web application running in a browser</a></li>
  <li>Sample queries using lite.datasette.io and the SUMO Firefox 2021 Desktop Support Question SQLite database at: <a href="https://rtanglao.github.io/rt-kits-api3/YEARLY_CSV_FILES/2021-firefox-sumo-questions.db">https://rtanglao.github.io/rt-kits-api3/YEARLY_CSV_FILES/2021-firefox-sumo-questions.db</a></li>
  <li>How to use it:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <ol>
          <li>Surf to <a href="https://lite.datasette.io">lite.datasette.io</a></li>
          <li>Click <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Load database by URL to a SQLite DB</code> and enter <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">https://rtanglao.github.io/rt-kits-api3/YEARLY_CSV_FILES/2021-firefox-sumo-questions.db</code> or any other URL of a SQLite file with CORS headers</li>
          <li>Click on the relevant table e.g. in this case <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2021-yearly-ff-questions-en-us</code> and then Enter your queries using SQLite’s SQL. Each query will have a unique URL which you can shre with others who can learn from it and do their own queries.</li>
          <li>Fame and fortune :-)</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Previously: February 21, 2021: <a href="http://rolandtanglao.com/2021/02/21/p1-everything-in-sqlitite-and-glitch/">Everything in SQLite and Datasette and perhaps Glitch?</a></li>
</ul>
